## Step 4 — Update the dev Function App name

Open deploy-dev.yml and replace `dev-p6-api-fa` with the actual name of your dev/QA Function App.

---

## Step 5 — Push and verify

```bash
# Commit the workflow changes on develop
git add .github/workflows/
git commit -m "ci: separate dev and prod deployment workflows"
git push origin develop
```

This will trigger the dev deployment automatically. Check **GitHub → Actions tab** to confirm it runs green.

---

## Step 6 — Releasing to prod (your normal flow going forward)

```bash
# When dev is tested and ready:
git checkout main
git merge develop
git push origin main     # triggers prod deployment automatically
```

GitHub Actions will deploy to `prod-p6-api-fa`. The dev function app is untouched.

---

## Step 7 (Optional but recommended) — Add a manual approval gate for prod

In GitHub → repo → **Settings → Environments**:
1. Create environment named `production`
2. Enable **Required reviewers** → add yourself
3. Now every push to `main` will pause and wait for your approval before deploying to prod

---

## Summary of what each environment controls independently

| Thing | Where it lives | Dev value | Prod value |
|---|---|---|---|
| P6 credentials | Azure App Settings | dev P6 server | prod P6 server |
| Blob containers | Azure App Settings | `p6-exports-dev` | `p6-exports` |
| Storage account | Azure App Settings | dev storage | `azp6sqlprd` |
| Timer schedules | Azure App Settings | different cadence | `0 0 10,17 * * *` |
| Code | Git branch | `develop` | `main` |

The code is always identical between environments. Only Azure App Settings differ.

