GitHub Copilot: The `THROW` statement in SQL Server does not accept expressions — the message must be a variable or literal. Need to assign to a variable first, then throw. 

Replacing 20 lines with 20 lines in [](file:///c%3A/Users/seethapn1094/OneDrive%20-%20ARCADIS/Documents/DataScience/NYPA/P6/NYPA_ADF/AzureP6Pipeline_V2/SQL/Populate_P6_Variance_Annual_From_Spread.sql), [](file:///c%3A/Users/seethapn1094/OneDrive%20-%20ARCADIS/Documents/DataScience/NYPA/P6/NYPA_ADF/AzureP6Pipeline_V2/SQL/Populate_P6_Variance_From_Spread.sql)


```

```

```

```
The root cause: SQL Server's `THROW` only accepts a string **variable** or literal for the message — not an inline concatenated expression. Fixed by assigning the built string to `@ThrowMsg1` first, then passing that variable to `THROW`. Both procedures are now corrected.

Made changes.

